based events.

3
00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:16.140
So they control internally scripted behaviors for in game actors and you can even control

4
00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:18.320
complex animations for game characters.

5
00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:23.560
So the blueprint system, you'll see these windows across many different editors, whether

6
00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:34.320
or even Niagara audio blueprints can be used to be the code driven driving block behind

7
00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:39.280
different real time interactions.

8
00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:41.280
So what are blueprints?

9
00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:45.720
So in their basic form blueprints are visual scripts that use to add new functionality

10
00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:50.200
to your game by connecting the nodes, events and functions, which is what you see in the

11
00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:53.640
images here with wires.

12
00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:58.720
So you can create some kind of intended interactive outcome.

13
00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:04.080
So you'll see that we have events which are setting these red nodes on the right hand

14
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:09.000
side and then you'll see some kind of function based gameplay.

15
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.640
So the functions are the blue node on the top right hand corner, for example, connected

16
00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:16.640
to some kind of variable data.

17
00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:22.000
So you'll see these wires connecting and it's almost like a chain of events.

18
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.820
You can follow the logic from left to right and get the intended outcome of what you want

19
00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:29.840
your blueprint to be.

20
00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:35.200
So we'll dive into the editor later in this course, but just to give you a bit of an overview

21
00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:39.100
of the interface you may expect to see inside of Unreal.

22
00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:45.320
So when we open our blueprint editor, which you can do by clicking the node graph on the

23
00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:51.080
top of your editor and just go to open level blueprint, you can see that.

24
00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:56.160
But just to dig into a bit more detail here, so we have the text menus on the top, which

25
00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:59.760
you'd expect to see across all of Unreal Engine.

26
00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:03.960
But the bar that you'll be using a lot is on this number two section here.

27
00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:09.960
So you have compile, which every time you're editing a blueprint or changing the functionality,

28
00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:15.000
you want to make sure you compile and save and it just keeps the iteration going.

29
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.320
You can ensure that although the code is working correctly and of course saving your

30
00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:24.560
work at frequent stages because especially when you're first getting familiar with blueprints

31
00:02:24.560 --> 00:02:30.360
and maybe you connect some nodes that may end up crashing or failing, you just want

32
00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.480
to keep that information safe so that if the editor does shut for whatever reason, you've

33
00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:36.560
not lost any work.

34
00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:43.560
We can browse content and find content and change settings slightly more complex.

35
00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:48.820
A good thing to point out on the right hand side here is you can debug information as

36
00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:49.820
well.

